The prevailing narrative may be that the last week of summer means markets are quiet, but as any analyst who covers European HY knows, the last week of August is decidedly unquiet and often relatively noisy. This week, we discuss reporting from Asda and Pernod Ricard as well as CBR and EG Group. We also unpack a plethora of UK macro data including the latest inflation report, Worldpanel by Numerator data for both food and apparel, BRC sales and more.
Soundbite of the Week: "We saw a clear improvement in performance during 2Q with volumes and LFL sales strengthening" Asda 2Q25 release

IG Consumer and Retail spreads took a breather this week, but were broadly in line with the overall market widening. YTD, the Food & Beverage sub- sector has underperformed the wider non- financials indices in both IG and HY, in spread terms, whilst Retail has marginally outperformed in IG but significantly so in HY, given the move in ELOFR (now CEETRU) spreads, in particular.

EBITDA includes £35m extra adjustment (Extended Producer Responsibility), which we understand to be related to the annualized impact of the increase in labour costs. This is an unprecedented adjustment without which underlying EBITDA would have fallen to £187m and thus much closer to our previous estimate - prior to 1Q25 publication - of £189m. LTM adj. EBITDA currently stands at £945m (vs £1.1bn at FY24), which increases to c. £1bn when accounting for the £70m synergies related to America and Arthur.

- FCF and balance sheet: 2Q25 FCF was -£12m (vs -£120m in 2Q24) supported by an additional £128m inflow from WC. PF for the effect of the SUNs refinancing that took place in June, net debt stood at £3.8bn (flat q/q and vs £3.6bn at FY24) with leverage ticking up to 3.8x from 3.4x at 1Q25 and 2.9x at FY24 due to the drop in LTM EBITDA. Liquidity remains solid at £1.4bn, comprising £793m undrawn RCF and £611m of PF available cash.

- Project Future and FY25 guidance: Asda believes it has now fully completed Project Future with the roll out being finalized in all stores and depots. The company has encountered some IT disruptions, which led to a reduction in product availability starting from the end of June. This led to a deviation from the improvement trajectory previously envisaged heading into 2H with a deterioration in LFL sales decline in 3Q to date (-1.8% and -1.6% LFL in July and August, respectively). Consequently, management downwardly revised FY25 guidance for EBITDA and FCF. While no precise indication on EBITDA has been provided (besides mentioning that the rate of y/y decline will sequentially reduce), company-defined FCF was previously guided to be around £600m, in line with FY24, supported by continued WC improvements. We have previously noted that we deemed this target to be quite ambitious. The company still expects to exit FY25 with positive LFL sales growth. Finally, Asda noted that it expects FY25 leverage to remain around the 2Q25 level (3.8x) and that, despite the lack of immediate maturities, it is still considering a S&L transaction with proceeds earmarked for debt paydown.
CBR Fashion 2Q25 results showed similar trends to 1Q25 and allowed for the reiteration of FY25 guidance for both revenue and profit growth, despite headwinds in the Retail channel.

- Operating performance: 2Q25 group revenues increased 7% y/y to €202m driven by diverging trends among the channels. Retail delivered 3% y/y revenue growth, but was entirely driven by perimeter expansion offsetting negative LFL impacted by lower footfall. Similarly, Wholesale revenues increased by 3%, while eCommerce rose by 19% despite strong comps and on increased marketing investments. 2Q25 adj. EBITDA increased €1m y/y to €46m, but with a margin contraction of 120bps y/y to 22.7%. Profits were negatively impacted mostly by the decline in LFL in Retail which caused a 5%-pt decline in the channel's GM, further impacted also by stock devaluation effects and higher sourcing costs.

- FCF and balance sheet: 2Q25 FCF was €28m (vs €32m in 2Q24) impacted by WC outflow. Net debt at quarter end was €419m (vs €447m at 1Q25) given FCF, with leverage ticking down to 2.7x (vs 2.9x at 1Q25 and 2.7x at 2Q24). Liquidity at quarter end amounted to €106m, comprising €51m cash and €57m undrawn RCF.

EG Group reported 2Q25 results impacted by continued weak performance in the US.

Operating performance: 2Q25 LFL sales declined \(4.5\%\) to \(\) 5.9\(bn impacted by the easing of demand for fuel in the US. US Fuel top line movement was driven by flat volumes (improving sequentially from - 3\% in 1Q25) and negative pricing, while the company noted a return to volume growth in July. LFL revenues increased +2.7\% in Grocery & Merchandise and +8.2\% in Foodservice on solid growth in Europe. 2Q25 EBITDA declined 1.1\% to\) \ \(268m\) mainly impacted by a \(24.6\%\) fall in the US on Fuel gross profit reduction.

FCF and balance sheet: Company- defined FCF was break even (vs \(\) 37m\(in 2Q24) with lower interest payments offset by lower inflow from WC and tax payments. Net debt stepped up to\) \ \(5.7bn\) (vs \(\) 5.5bn\(at 1Q25) impacted by FX movements, with leverage now standing at 5.6x (vs 5.2x previously). PF for the announced sale of the Italian and Australian businesses, LTM EBITDA stands instead at\) \ \(852m\) (vs \(\) 1bn\(currently) and leverage at 5.2x. EG also noted that in 1H25 it signed agreements to sell underperforming sites and a fuel depot in France with expected net proceeds of\) \in 23m\(and a further\) \in 60m\(is expected to be confirmed going forward. All disposal proceeds will be devoted to deleveraging.

Pernod Ricard published FY25 results (to the end of June) with slightly better top line growth in 4Q and profits in the full year. FY26 guidance was reiterated, but commentary highlighted weak F1Q26 expectations (to the end of September).

Operating performance: F4Q25 organic revenues were flat (vs BBG cons of - \(0.8\%\) ), improving sequentially compared to \(- 3\%\) in F3Q25. Overall, FY25 organic revenues declined by \(3\%\) (vs cons of \(- 3.2\%\) ), on \(- 5\%\) price/mix and \(+2\%\) volumes. Organic revenues ex. USA and China increased \(1\%\) . FY25 organic EBIT declined \(0.8\%\) to €2.95bn (vs BBG cons of €2.91bn), with 64bp yoy organic margin expansion on GM decline (- 50bp driven by negative mix) offset by 17bp decline in Structure costs and 97bp in A&P spending. FY25 EBIT at actual FX declined \(5.3\%\) , impacted by FX (Turkish lira, Nigerian Naira, British Pound and Argentinean peso).

Divisional Performance: Among Pernod's key markets, the US and China remained weak, partly offset by continued growth in India. Americas FY25 organic sales declined by \(3\%\) y/y driven by the US \((- 6\%)\) and Mexico (- LSD%), which were not fully offset by growth in Canada and Brazil. Pernod noted that prolonged tariff uncertainty impacted distributor inventory levels at year end with some adjustments expected through FY26. EBIT in the region was flat y/y at €847m. Europe sales declined organically by \(2\%\) on resilient sales in Eastern Europe and France offset by a decline in Germany and Spain. EBIT declined by \(1\%\) y/y to €744m. Asia/ROW organic sales declined \(4\%\) driven by \(- 21\%\) in China, partially offset by strong momentum in India (+6%) on solid consumer demand and premiumization trends. China performance continued to be impacted by the challenging macro- economic environment and weak consumer demand. A strong decline is expected in 1Q due to inventory overhang at the end of the year. EBIT declined \(1\%\) organically to €1.4bn. Amongst the brands, Strategic International Brands saw organic revenue decline of \(4\%\) , impacted by a sharp decline in Martell in China, while Strategic Local Brands \(+2\%\) and Specialty Brands \(- 7\%\) . Finally, Global Travel Retail organic revenues also declined by \(14\%\) mostly impacted by the suspension of duty- free regime on Cognac in China, which should however be resolved from F2Q26.

FCF/Net Debt: FY25 company- defined FCF was €1.1bn (vs €963m in FY24) with lower profits offset by WC inflow. Net debt declined €10.7bn (vs €10.9bn at FY24) with leverage now at \(3.3x\) (vs \(3.1x\) at FY24) due to profit contraction.

Guidance: FY26 is expected to be a transition year with "improving trends" in top line, albeit skewed towards 2H. A revenue decline is expected in 1Q (vs BBG cons \(+0.3\%\) ) due to inventory adjustments in the US, continued weakness in China, some excise policy changes in India and the Duty Free Cognac sales in China resuming only in 2Q. Pernod reiterated its intention to defend margins, similarly to this year, and to improve cash conversion. The medium- term targets, previously revised in February, have been reiterated for organic revenues growth of \(3\%\) to \(6\%\) , accompanied by organic EBIT margin expansion driven by €1bn efficiencies from FY26 to FY29. Finally, the full annualized impact of tariffs has now been quantified at €80m, comprising €35m in relation to the US and €45m in relation to the minimum price undertaking on cognac in China.

Suedzucker Guidance cutSuedzucker issued a profit warning, reducing guidance for FY26 top line, EBITDA and EBIT due to a cut in profit expectations across three of its divisions (Sugar, CropEnergies and Special Products). The company had already flagged in July a slow start of F2Q26 sales (ending August '26) expecting a significant y/y decline in EBITDA and EBIT in the quarter (vs €190m and €114m in F2Q25, respectively).

Guidance: The company is now guiding for FY26 revenues of €8.3bn- to- €8.7bn (vs €8.7bn- to- €9.2bn previously vs €9.7bn in FY25), FY26 EBITDA of €470m- to- €570m (vs €525m- to- €675m previously vs €723m in FY25) and FY26 EBIT of €100m- to- €200m (vs €150m- to- €300m previously vs €350m in FY25).

Sugar division: The company had previously noted that its FY26 guidance rested on the assumption that EU sugar price level would improve considerably in the next marketing year (October 2025 to September 2026, i.e. F2H26 for the company). We note that Sugar is Suedzucker's biggest division, accounting for c.40% of group revenues, and that the previous divisional guidance included EBIT loss of €100m- to- €200m for FY26 on weaker F1H26 partially offset by a return to profit in F2H26. We therefore think that the cut makes the return of the Sugar division to profitability less likely in F2H26.

Credit considerations: The release didn't provide any updates on FY26 net debt expectations, while it previously included an expected reduction in FY26 vs FY25's €1.7bn. Assuming FY26 EBITDA of €520m (mid- point of the guided range) and unchanged net debt position (rather than a decline y/y), we estimate an increase in leverage to 3.3x in FY26 from 2.3x in FY25. As of F1Q26, the company retained a solid liquidity position of €3.2bn.
F1H26 results will be published on 9 October.

BAT announced that CFO Soraya Benchich is stepping down with immediate effect after only fifteen months in the role without providing further details around the reasons for her departure. A recruitment process to fill the position has been launched, while Javed Iqbal will take on the role in the interim. Iqbal currently holds the role of Director of Digital and Information and had previously acted as Interim Finance Director between 2023 and 2024.

Within the same release, BAT confirmed it was "firmly on track to deliver" its FY25 guidance for revenue growth of \(1\% - 0 - 2\%\) (vs cons of \(+1.6\%\) and \(+1.3\%\) in FY24) and underlying profit growth of \(1.5\% - 0 - 2.5\%\) (vs cons. \(+2.2\%\) and \(+1.4\%\) in FY24). We recall that BAT's ambitions include a return to its medium- term guidance trajectory by 2026 (3%- to- 5% revenue growth and 4%- to- 6% adj. EBIT growth on an organic basis at constant FX) and a return to within its leverage target corridor of 2.0x- to- 2.5x (vs 2.4x at FY24 or 2.75x as adjusted for the Canadian impact) by the end of 2026.

The FDA has issued an MDO (marketing denial order - here) for Imperial Brands' blu Disposable Classic Tobacco \(2.4\%\) . The decision was based on the grounds that the company didn't provide sufficient evidence that adult smokers will completely switch to the new product and reduce their cigarette consumption with evidence suggesting dual

use of this product in addition to cigarettes. The MDO implies that the company will not be able to offer these products in the US. We note that the US currently accounts for \(35\%\) of Imperial's revenues, which are generated entirely through combustibles, and that IMBLN is already lagging behind peers Philip Morris and BAT in NGP development with only \(4\%\) of its revenues currently generated from these products (vs \(39\%\) and \(13\%\) for PM and BAT, respectively in FY24). The company had already previously flagged limited investment in US vapour given the market uncertainty caused by a lack of visibility on regulatory enforcement against illicit trade (an issue that has also been flagged by other competitors, especially BAT).

Premier Foods announced the acquisition of premium meal brand Merchant Gourmet from its founding shareholders at an EV of £48m, on a cash free and debt free basis. The brand is expected to generate £28m in revenues in the year to March '26 and is said to have delivered DD% growth over the last two years. The company did not disclose the EBITDA of the business, but, given the disclosed HSD EV/EBITDA multiple and £48m valuation, we would assume it to be in the £5m- to- £7m range. Premier Foods had previously flagged its intention to engage in more M&A going forward, but this is a relatively small acquisition given the substantial liquidity position of the company (£283m undrawn RCF and £192m cash) and the limited PF leverage impact (only 0.2x vs 0.7x at FY25 and 1.5x leverage target).

Kantar France GroceryKantar France FMCG Sales (by value) increased by \(0.4\%\) y/y in the four weeks to 10 August 2025 (08P25), deteriorating compared to \(+4.2\%\) y/y in 07P25. Food prices increased by \(1.6\%\) y/y in July (vs \(+1.4\%\) y/y in June) with the implied volume/mix falling into negative territory to \(- 1.2\%\) y/y from \(+2.6\%\) y/y in the previous print. Among the formats, hypermarkets lost 20bps market share y/y, improving significantly compared to the 70bps lost in the previous print, while online continued to perform well, gaining 40bps y/y. Convenience's market share increased by 10bps y/y, while discounters' by 20bps y/y. After months of market share growth following the Cora & Match acquisition, Carrefour lost 10bps y/y in this print. Intermarche continued to deliver solid gains with a market share increase of 30bps. Auchan's market share declined in this print once again by 40bps y/y to \(9\%\) , impacted by a perimeter reduction. Casino lost 20bps of market share y/y in this print, while Leclerc gained 20bps y/y.

CEBR's Asda Income Tracker for July saw UK average household discretionary income grow by 2.4% y/y to £255 per week (vs £252 in June). This therefore presents the

second consecutive month of deceleration \((+3.8\%)\) y/y in June). CEBR noted that this was mainly driven by a further pick- up in inflation in July (CPI printed at \(+3.8\%\) y/y in July vs \(+3.6\%\) y/y in June), mostly driven by rising costs for food and transportation. The month's reading is still slightly above the 2024 annual average (f243), which has recovered significantly from the 2022 and 2023 average levels (f216 and f218, respectively).

Among the quintiles, we note that average weekly discretionary income has risen for the higher quintiles (4th and 5th), while it has fallen for the lowest income groups, which for the first time since September 2023 also include the third quintile \((- 1.6\%)\) . The lowest income quintile continued to record negative average weekly discretionary income. Going forward, CEBR continues to see real wage growth driving persistent annual growth in the Income Tracker, albeit at a more moderate pace.
